06:45.460 --> 06:48.380
Many of Sturgeon's people are, in some sense of the word, misfits.

06:48.840 --> 06:49.800
They are searching for something.

06:50.320 --> 06:51.240
They're incomplete somehow.

06:51.660 --> 06:53.440
And they're usually different than others around them.

06:53.440 --> 06:56.300
The characters in Sturgeon's novel, More Than Human, are good examples.

06:56.740 --> 06:56.920
Right.

06:57.200 --> 07:01.700
That work is built around an idiot, a pair of orphaned twins, an adolescent girl, and

07:01.700 --> 07:04.000
a mongoloid baby, all outcast from society.

07:04.400 --> 07:07.140
Many of Sturgeon's other stories have misfits as their protagonists, too.

07:07.480 --> 07:08.120
We asked him why.

07:08.900 --> 07:11.900
Well, I think a misfit has a chance to be objective.

07:12.960 --> 07:20.520
And for one thing, he sees society as a whole from its underbelly or from way off at one

07:20.520 --> 07:20.960
side.

07:23.480 --> 07:25.240
Essentially, it's not so much misfits.

07:26.160 --> 07:28.300
The key to what I write I think is loneliness.

07:29.940 --> 07:33.440
I learned early that you can write about excitement.

07:33.680 --> 07:34.680
You can write about adventure.

07:34.860 --> 07:36.600
You can write love and sex and so on.

07:37.180 --> 07:41.860
And basically, in each case, you don't hit too many people.

07:42.040 --> 07:45.480
But if you write about loneliness, everybody's an expert.

07:47.100 --> 07:52.040
I'm fond of saying that if you know some guy who collects pheasant feathers, and that's

07:52.040 --> 07:56.560
his whole preoccupation, and you write a story that involves pheasant feathers, and you

07:56.560 --> 07:58.220
know what you're talking about, he's going to love it.

07:58.900 --> 08:02.940
But the incidence of people in the general population who collect pheasant feathers is

08:02.940 --> 08:03.600
very small.

08:05.120 --> 08:11.980
But the point is that because you wrote to an expert of an expertise, if you grab it,

08:11.980 --> 08:17.440
now what are people as a whole mostly expert at loneliness?

08:19.440 --> 08:21.540
The world is full of experts on loneliness.

08:21.820 --> 08:25.040
It's something that everybody recognizes when he sees it.

08:25.100 --> 08:29.740
So it's not so much that these people are misfits, it's that they're lonely.

08:30.600 --> 08:33.500
And I think that that's the hook that I can throw into people the hardest.

08:34.720 --> 08:37.280
Sturgeon tries to counter this loneliness with love.

08:37.820 --> 08:41.780
He often has his characters lose their loneliness by experiencing love of some sort.

08:42.100 --> 08:46.340
But readers should be warned that it may not be the kind of love they're used to reading about or seeing on the movie screen.

08:46.660 --> 08:47.100
Not always.

08:47.360 --> 08:52.340
The world well lost and case and the dreamer are two of the stories that concern very different sorts of love.

08:52.780 --> 08:58.900
One of Sturgeon's best known stories is the powerful statement on love and compassion, though it's the highest sort of love given to the whole human race.

08:59.340 --> 09:04.120
The story is called Thunder and Roses, and it was published not long after the atomic bomb was dropped on Hiroshima.

09:04.120 --> 09:10.400
The United States has been devastated by nuclear attack, and the last American military installation that could retaliate chooses not to.

09:10.760 --> 09:14.000
The reason is to save humanity, to give our species a chance to rebuild.

09:14.520 --> 09:15.640
Sturgeon talks about the story.

09:16.060 --> 09:20.260
That's a very interesting story. That was written when the death was still settling over Hiroshima.

09:21.120 --> 09:25.900
It's probably the first atomic boom story that was written after the bomb was dropped.

09:27.400 --> 09:30.140
It was written in late 1945.

09:32.940 --> 09:35.220
I wrote that with considerable passion.

09:36.040 --> 09:41.460
There wasn't anybody in the world who understood what had happened, except the people in the science fiction fraternity,

09:41.840 --> 09:47.360
and maybe one or two rather forward-thinking scientists at Oak Ridge and the state of Washington.

09:48.400 --> 09:52.100
And for the rest of the world, it's just another big bang.

09:53.460 --> 09:56.520
But in science fiction, there, John Campbell had been publishing

09:57.420 --> 10:00.880
Atomic Power and Atomic War stories for 15 years before that.

10:01.740 --> 10:03.640
And we all understood what had happened.

10:03.780 --> 10:10.540
Every single person who'd been writing or reading science fiction understood precisely what had happened and what it meant to the world.

10:11.940 --> 10:15.660
Now, of course, it's become very much in the forefront, but we also are coming.

10:18.120 --> 10:18.920
Very bad.

10:20.200 --> 10:21.480
An ugly situation.

10:22.760 --> 10:26.320
Sturgeon says he gets a lot of response about the story and it's been reprinted many times.

10:27.260 --> 10:32.360
As a matter of fact, Ben Bober was just about to publish it in Atomic as a classic when he left.

10:32.940 --> 10:36.460
And I don't know what the situation is for the story again, but his chances at it will show up there.

